  "prompt": "Can you state the law of conservation of mass?",
  "response": "Certainly! The **Law of Conservation of Mass** states that **mass is neither created nor destroyed in a chemical reaction**. This means that the total mass of the reactants (substances going into the reaction) is equal to the total mass of the products (substances produced by the reaction). This principle was first clearly formulated by the French chemist Antoine Lavoisier in the late 18th century.\n\nIn mathematical terms:\n\nMass of reactants = Mass of products\n\nThis law is a fundamental principle in chemistry and physics, and it applies to all closed systems where matter is not allowed to enter or leave. It also forms the basis for balancing chemical equations.",
